## Task 5 — Practice, Practice, Practice

Hands-on practice using the Extractors, Date/Time, and Data Format categories.

### Extractors
| Operation | Purpose |
|---|---|
| Extract IP addresses | Pulls all valid IPv4/IPv6 addresses |
| Extract URLs | Pulls URLs (requires protocol prefix to avoid false positives) |
| Extract email addresses | Pulls anything matching `user@domain.tld` |

### Date / Time
| Operation | Purpose |
|---|---|
| To UNIX Timestamp | Converts UTC datetime string → UNIX timestamp |
| From UNIX Timestamp | Converts UNIX timestamp → readable datetime |

A UNIX timestamp = seconds elapsed since **Jan 1, 1970 UTC** (epoch).

### Data Format (Base Encodings)
| Operation | Description | Example |
|---|---|---|
| From Base64 | Decodes Base64 → raw text | `V2VsY29tZSB0byB0cnloYWNrbWUh` → `Welcome to tryhackme!` |
| URL Decode | Percent-decodes back to raw | `https%3A%2F%2F...` → `https://...` |
| From Base85 | More space-efficient than Base64 | `BOu!rD]j7BEbo7` → `hello world` |
| From Base58 | Drops ambiguous chars (`l`,`I`,`0`,`O`) | `AXLU7qR` → `Thm58` |
| To Base62 | Restricted symbol set, shorter output | `Thm62` → `6NiRkOY` |

**Manual Base64 encoding walkthrough ("THM"):**
1. Convert to 8-bit binary: `T`=`01010100`, `H`=`01001000`, `M`=`01001101`
2. Concatenate → `010101000100100001001101` (24 bits)
3. Split into 6-bit groups → `010101 000100 100001 001101`
4. Convert each group to decimal → `21, 4, 33, 13`
5. Map to Base64 index table → `V, E, h, N`
6. Result: **`VEhN`**

